Question: TextVisibility change after a period of time: :, I have just started learning java for android, I have set the TextVisibility of a textfield to GONE, I need the TextVisibilty to change to VISIBLE after 7 seconds from Button click, I had searched the internet and could not find anything useful or I could'nt understand. So, Please help me.
Please using this api: Activity.setContentView.
Answer:<<<api>>>: TextView.postDelayed
<<<code>>>: 
Button button = findViewById(R.id.button);
button.setOnClickListener(new View.OnClickListener() {
    @Override
    public void onClick(View v) {
        TextView textView = findViewById(R.id.textView);
        textView.setVisibility(View.VISIBLE);
        textView.postDelayed(new Runnable() {
            @Override
            public void run() {
                textView.setVisibility(View.GONE);
            }
        }, 7000);
    }
});
<<<explanation>>>: The postDelayed() method of the TextView class is used to post a Runnable to the message queue, to be run after the specified amount of time. In this case, we are setting the TextView to VISIBLE when the button is clicked, and then after 7 seconds (7000 milliseconds), we are setting it to GONE.
Question: How can I create a custom dialog in Android?
Please using this api: AlertDialog.Builder.
Answer:<<<api>>>: AlertDialog.Builder
<<<code>>>: 
AlertDialog.Builder builder = new AlertDialog.Builder(this);
builder.setTitle("Custom Dialog");
builder.setMessage("This is a custom dialog");
builder.setPositiveButton("OK", new DialogInterface.OnClickListener() {
    @Override
    public void onClick(DialogInterface dialog, int which) {
        dialog.dismiss();
    }
});
AlertDialog dialog = builder.create();
dialog.show();
<<<explanation>>>: The AlertDialog.Builder class is used to create a custom dialog. We can set a title, a message, and buttons. In this case, we are creating a dialog with a title, a message, and a single "OK" button. When the button is clicked, the dialog is dismissed.
Question: How can I create a custom adapter for a ListView?
Please using this api: ArrayAdapter.
Answer:<<<api>>>: ArrayAdapter
<<<code>>>: 
String[] fruits = {"Apple", "Banana", "Cherry", "Date", "Elderberry"};
ArrayAdapter<String> adapter = new ArrayAdapter<>(this, android.R.layout.simple_list_item_1, fruits);
ListView listView = findViewById(R.id.listView);
listView.setAdapter(adapter);
<<<explanation>>>: The ArrayAdapter class is used to create a custom adapter for a ListView. We can specify the layout for the rows of the ListView, and the data to be displayed. In this case, we are creating an ArrayAdapter for a ListView that displays an array of fruit names.
